          <div style="margin-left: 0px; position: relative; width: 1100px; z-index: 5; " id="body_layer">
            <div style="height: 0px; line-height: 0px; " class="bumper"> </div>
            <div id="id2" style="height: 86px; left: 23px; position: absolute; top: 26px; width: 939px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_939_86" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">Consider a quanto option, a call on Nikkei Dow Index, but paid in USD. Ignoring the PDE derivation there is an extra term in the final equation which is  <br /></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div id="id3" style="height: 128px; left: 177px; position: absolute; top: 120px; width: 480px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_480_128" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_1">-rho x sigma($) x sigma(yen) x S(DowIndex) x E(Exchange Rate)<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_1"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_1">This arises due to the increment of Delta x S(DowIndex) *E(ExchangeRate). So instead of having the usual r x S x delta, we have <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_1"><br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_1">(r(yenrate) - rho x sigma(dollar) x sigma(yen)) x S(DowIndex)</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div style="height: 100px; width: 100px;  height: 100px; left: 35px; position: absolute; top: 120px; width: 100px; z-index: 1; " class="tinyText">
              <div style="position: relative; width: 100px; ">
                <img src="Quantos_files/shapeimage_1.png" alt="" style="height: 100px; left: 0px; position: absolute; top: 0px; width: 100px; " />
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div id="id4" style="height: 190px; left: 35px; position: absolute; top: 280px; width: 867px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_867_190" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">A book has regular rho’s being computed in buckets for all the positions. In the above example we might have rho stress for a single bucket USD ‘200million’ and YEN ‘300million’. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">The term “<span style="line-height: 20px; " class="style">rho x sigma(dollar) x sigma(yen)” </span>is covariance, so if it rises by some amount this gets subtracted from r(yenrate), and decreases the rho Pnl. Scary part is that if covariance just increases by one percent we lose 300 million. This actually happened during 2008 coz Implied Correlation jumped from 20% to 60%. I haven’t come across any book which explains this practical scenario. </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div id="id5" style="height: 139px; left: 35px; position: absolute; top: 503px; width: 878px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_878_139" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">A good hedge for above position is simply a covariance swap. A covariance swap between Nikkei Dow Index and USD/YEN needs to be bought to hedge this risk. Even if you consider taking huge bumps while pricing to incorporate the costs, it doesn’t solve the problem. </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


